Last week, during the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as twentieth member of this agency, it is the second Member state of the ancient Eastern block (the Czech Republic became full member on November 12th, 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the course of the years which followed participated in a number of plans of the agency.
The road of Poland towards the space however started much more early.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always meet understanding.
I would like to recall conference for example of A. Š ternfeld in the astronomic observatory of Warsaw, on December 6th, 1933, in the course of which he introduced ideas drawn of his progressive called work "Introduction to astronautics".
Developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and of years later Š ternfeld remembered that alone the doctor Jan Gadomski was interested in his jobs.
In 1934, Š ternfeld got price in France Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for the work "Introduction to astronautics".
Aforementioned doctor Jan Gadomski (on 1899 - 1966) became later a big proponent of astronomy and of astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many works dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a proponent of world-famous astronautics, the contribution was notably rewarded due to the fact that the name was given to one of the craters of the face hidden from the Moon.
From 1925 was constructed in Poland a track inspection car intended to be equipped with an engine rocket.
Neither the author nor the details of this plan are unfortunately known.
He is not clear either if the rocket had to serve for projecting or for slowing down the track inspection car.
The only information known on this track inspection car is those of the press of epoch.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began dedicating itself to rockets.
Researches were performed by the institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with the professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It emerges from kept documents that this research had attained the stadium of trials.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, researches stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a rocket of photoelectric hunt, drawn by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialised press and next year was published work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two plans had as purpose a military usage of the engines of rockets.
Just before war, all plans of use of the technology of rockets were led by the interim advisory scientific committee (" Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy "), which co-ordinated all jobs.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of functioning, the beginning of war put an end to its activities.
After the war, other jobs dedicated to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the society Polish astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a matter of a society in the number of November, 1954 of the newspaper Problem, in which are four more detailed articles dedicated to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by the professor Mr Subotowicze, it is offered to create a society dedicated to astronautics
At that time, plans of artificial satellites had been already thrown and it was clear that the domain of space research had future.
At the beginning of the year on 1956, the society Polish astronautics (PTA) made efforts to enter international astronautics in the federation (created in 1951) and from autumn, PTA became a regular member.
Next year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (on 1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the federation international astronautics.
He kept his function up to his death in 1959.
From 1956, PTA brought a significant contribution in the development crowned with success of the meteorological rocket RM (RAKIETA METEOROLOGICZNA), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific researches.
The first model, RM-1, was ended in 1957 and the first launching took place on October 10th, 1958.
This rocket of a 1800-metre range had a 80 cm length and weighed 5 a little less than kg.
Later was constructed an improved version, RM-1A and, during summer, 1959, trials of flight of the two-storeyed rocket RM-2 was started in the desert of Bledov.
This rocket had a 1,4-metre length and weighed probably 11,5 kg.
Following archetype should have been capable of doing concrete scientific works - the rocket RM-34 should have had a range going up to 14,5 km and to serve for noticing the wind in altitude.
But in 1963, all jobs of development were stopped.
The rocket Meteor-1 perfected in the course of period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of type RM.
This rocket, conceived with two floors, had a complete length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32,5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A,-1B and-1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the space reserved for the scientific tools.
The rocket Meteor-1A had a space giving a 0,4-litre volume, while in Meteor-1B this volume litre and in 0,62-litre Meteor-1C was 0,34.
The maximum range of all these types of device was 37 km.
For the period 1965 - On 1968, rockets Meteor-2 were perfected in the aicraft institute, the first trials of flight started in October, 1970.
The rocket Meteor-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of transporting a payload from 10 kg to an altitude about 60 km.
Later were constructed Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions.
It is still necessary to mention the entrance of Poland in COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
As part of the programme Interkosmos, Poland also participated in space exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
