The hardest job of the world: the human female mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euro, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and their health by carrying 70 kilogrammes of sulphur across the abrupt stony tracks.
There are people for whom job is a Hell and others who work literally in Hell.
It is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by carrying the sulphur of the volcano Kawah Ijen, east of the Indonesian island of Popular dance.
He must work every day up to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas emanating from bowels of the earth solidifies in the contact of air.
Having harvested big rocks of sulphur, which weigh in total about 70 kilogrammes, he instal them in two baskets in bamboo which he loads on his shoulders across the abrupt tracks.
There are only 250 metres up to the peak of the volcano which culminates as in altitude as 2,386 metres, but the exhausted bearers put more than 40 minutes to climb up this distance, in turtle's pace, by keeping balance and measuring their steps not to stumble and fall in precipice.
They know that a mistake could cost them life, as it arrived at a French tourist who made a lethal fall in the volcano Kawah Ijen several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for every kilogramme of extracted sulphur.
Once above, him elbow in between the tourists who photograph them as though they were animals of circus, and carrying barely the heavy baskets, they walk 3 kilometres up to the balance that a mining society installed a bit down below in 1,850 metres in altitude.
It is about PT CANDI NGRIMBI, a firm which exploits the volcano since 1960 and, it is possible to say it, her employees, to whom she pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) by kilogramme of sulphur.
She sells it then in 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro) in petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and used to fabricate candles, fireworks, beauty products, dynamite and serves even for whitening the sugar.
"As we transport about 70 kilogrammes, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3,8 euro) in every trip", explains us Anto, who performs three trips in general a day.
Each gets from him 3 hours and he ends exhausted, but it allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11,50 euro) at the end of the day.
Although it appears to be a misery for such superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would earn in fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the harvest of the coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1,20 euro) a day and when the monthly average wage is two million rupees (167 euro)", declares the bearer who worked in the past as bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, the wage was 75,000 rupees (6,20 euro) a day and the work was not also difficult, but Anto came back near the family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason which, in Indonesia, is also unquestionable as the sulphur: "I married a girl of Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Popular dance so that she becomes a convert to Islam".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, always coughs and the eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
