The summit also ended with the joint agreement of Chile and of Peru to accept a judgement of the Court of The Hague which cuts a different person living near the border between both countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during regional appointment and declared that they would respect the decision of CIJ to hear the advocacies of both parts in the trial which Lima began against Santiago and that begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and carry out the verdict which will solve disagreement which we carry in front of this International Court today", declared the president Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was always, and will continue being a respectful country of international law, of peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and of international courts", added the president Piñera by giving a handshake to the president Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they would submit in CIJ took place after Colombia reports this week the Pact of Bogota by which she had agreed to submit to decisions of this international court, after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua which she considered as gravely erroneous.
